    <span class="author" data-post-author="RicDrywall"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=367293&amp;sid=a03e3d6c8a15eef9ff6d5db9a8a5be3b">RicDrywall</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Centurion</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2014/03/dual-boot-phones-the-answer-to-a-question-that-nobody-is-asking/?comments=1&post=26431657#comment-26431657" title="2014-03-13T15:48:20-05:00" class="timeago datetime">Thu Mar 13, 2014 2:48 pm</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26431407#p26431407" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">DrPizza</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26431383#p26431383" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">AdamM</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Don't you just love setting up your smartphone? Entering account details, downloading apps, putting all the settings just the way you like them? Isn't this experience so wonderful that you want to do it twice?<br /><br />Wouldn't the smartphone experience just be so much better if it had two entirely different sets of apps? Apps that couldn't talk to each other, didn't even acknowledge each other's existence? Apps that burn up the already limited smartphone storage?<br /><br />And who doesn't relish the opportunity to reboot their smartphone several times a day to switch between operating systems?</div><br /><br />To people who need apps on both platforms what makes this any different than dual booting PC's?<br /><br />I could literally replace smartphone with computer in every instance and it would still work.</div><br />Yes. Yes you could.</div><br /><br />And in modern PCs, where processors are designed with specialized support for virtualization and RAM and disk storage are ample, I'm hard-pressed to think of a situation where dual-booting is worth it over running a virtual machine with the secondary OS (outside of a few specific cases where you still need direct hardware access on the second OS).
      
    </div>
