    <span class="author" data-post-author="Mitlov"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=335044&amp;sid=a03e3d6c8a15eef9ff6d5db9a8a5be3b">Mitlov</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Tribunus Militum</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2014/03/dual-boot-phones-the-answer-to-a-question-that-nobody-is-asking/?comments=1&post=26431669#comment-26431669" title="2014-03-13T15:49:05-05:00" class="timeago datetime">Thu Mar 13, 2014 2:49 pm</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      I prefer Windows Phone to Android for my day-to-day phone tasks--facebook, taking pictures of my kids, text-messaging, etc.  Yet my workplace, a bring-your-own-device workplace, requires iOS or Android for remote access of work email.<br /><br />Dual-booting phones are far from ideal, but they're better than my current situation, which is using an OS I'm less enthusiastic about 100% of the time because I need it instead of Windows Phone 10% of the time.
      
        <p class="edited">Last edited by <a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=335044&amp;sid=a03e3d6c8a15eef9ff6d5db9a8a5be3b">Mitlov</a> on Thu Mar 13, 2014 2:49 pm</p>
      
