    <span class="author" data-post-author="qazwart"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=330319&amp;sid=a03e3d6c8a15eef9ff6d5db9a8a5be3b">qazwart</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Centurion</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2014/03/dual-boot-phones-the-answer-to-a-question-that-nobody-is-asking/?comments=1&post=26431725#comment-26431725" title="2014-03-13T15:55:31-05:00" class="timeago datetime">Thu Mar 13, 2014 2:55 pm</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      I can't see too many people using dual boot phones. It's a feature that 999 people out of 1000 wouldn't care about and the other 1 out of 1000 wouldn't want.<br /><br />However, I could see this being an advantage to both the manufacturers and the stores: You only have one item of inventory. No need to stock both the Android and Windows version. Once you boot the phone and select your OS, you can't switch to the other without completely reseting the phone. This way, there's no need for double the RAM since it isn't shared between operating systems.
      
    </div>
