    <span class="author" data-post-author="breze"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=415547&amp;sid=a03e3d6c8a15eef9ff6d5db9a8a5be3b">breze</a></span><span class="rank">Smack-Fu Master, in training</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2014/03/dual-boot-phones-the-answer-to-a-question-that-nobody-is-asking/?comments=1&post=26431891#comment-26431891" title="2014-03-13T16:12:10-05:00" class="timeago datetime">Thu Mar 13, 2014 3:12 pm</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      Perhaps android could be configured to import configuration data from WP, or vice-verse?<br /><br />Also, it would be cool* if they could emulate WP from android and vice-verse, and have dual boot, so you could hop to emulator for small tasks and reboot if you really need. The disadvantages of dual boot are the product of having loosely coupled os's on the same device -- all the redundancies. Since the manufacturer is setting this up they can do the extra work and make the environments work together. Or they could do minimal work to get a hunk of junk out the door, like every OEM ever. <br /><br />*I would not actually pay for this
      
    </div>
