    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26431851#p26431851" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">bburdge</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26431815#p26431815" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">artifex</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">A secondary OS like WP8 would be an interesting fallback position if you're worried your manufacturer will abandon Android upgrades and support for your phone soon after selling it to you (like HTC seems to do). Does Microsoft push updates on its own, or does it require manufacturer and telco approval?</div><br />So the answer is, &quot;yes, if you ask for it.&quot;<br /><br />MS has a system where anyone who wants early update access can register a free &quot;developer&quot; account and add an app to their phone that pushes new OS updates as soon as they are available. So, anyone who's interested in keeping up-to-date can do so.</div><br /><br />Sounds good to me. Direct updates is a feature I admire about the Apple phones: it should be my choice whether to attempt updating to a new version of an OS if my hardware can handle it, and I shouldn't have to roll my own ROM if I'm not on a flagship, either.
      
    </div>
